   152â†’## FAQ<a name="faq"></a>
   153â†’
   154â†’### Why this parser?<a name="why-this-parser"></a>
   155â†’
   156â†’- it's lil'
   157â†’- pure Python with zero dependencies
   158â†’- the fastest pure Python parser [\*](#pure-python):
   159â†’  14x as fast as [tomlkit](https://pypi.org/project/tomlkit/),
   160â†’  2.1x as fast as [toml](https://pypi.org/project/toml/)
   161â†’- outputs [basic data types](#how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types) only
   162â†’- 100% spec compliant: passes all tests in
   163â†’  [toml-lang/toml-test](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml-test)
   164â†’  test suite
   165â†’- thoroughly tested: 100% branch coverage
   166â†’
   167â†’### Is comment preserving round-trip parsing supported?<a name="is-comment-preserving-round-trip-parsing-supported"></a>
   168â†’
   169â†’No.
   177â†’### Is there a `dumps`, `write` or `encode` function?<a name="is-there-a-dumps-write-or-encode-function"></a>
   178â†’
   179â†’[Tomli-W](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli-w) is the write-only counterpart of Tomli, providing `dump` and `dumps` functions.
   183â†’### How do TOML types map into Python types?<a name="how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types"></a>
   184â†’
   185â†’| TOML type        | Python type         | Details                                                      |
   201â†’## Performance<a name="performance"></a>
   202â†’
   203â†’The `benchmark/` folder in this repository contains a performance benchmark for comparing the various Python TOML parsers.
